node.text:
Here is a perfect example on how to swaddle your newborn! ✨The @embebabies starter swaddle is for babies 0-3 months, and includes adjustable lengths to grow with your baby. Ensure you are always swaddling 3 inches below the shoulders, and wrapping nice and snug. 
Any swaddling questions?! Comment below, and tag a mama who needs one!❤️

node.title: How to Swaddle Your Baby (0-3 months)

node.text:
“It’s been 5 weeks and I can still FEEL this picture.⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
After 36 hours of labour - he was in my arms. While everyone around me was cleaning and doing paperwork, time stood still as I fed him for the first time. The adrenaline was wearing off, the epidural was losing its effect and my whole body was dead weight. I was the most exhausted I’d ever been in my entire life - and it was so worth it.⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
I asked my husband to take lots of pictures this time around. I wanted to remember every moment. The good, the bad, the excitement, the pain and everything else that comes with child birth. It all happens so quickly - in the grand scheme of things. You spend 9 months growing a human and within days or sometimes hours - you’ve gone through the entire birth process. With all of the emotions that come along with birth - the hormones, adrenaline, fear, chaos - it’s easy to forget and appreciate what your body just did.⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
It’s easy to forget the special moments like this.⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
I didn’t know he had taken this picture.. and the first time I saw it, I felt so overwhelmed with emotion. It brought me right back to that moment. One that I probably would have forgotten all about."⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀

📷 @terriannmichelle

node.text:
Ah, these early days home. Soaking in every exhausting, beautiful, scary, exhilarating moment. Hours upon hours staring down at you❤️

What is one must have product that helped you or baby through the first couple weeks at home?! 👇🏼

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by embé® swaddles ✨ in Phoenix, Arizona. May be an image of 1 person and child.

node.text:
"Some days and nights still feel so empty. Like who you were is gone. The life you had is gone. And what your identity was has completely changed.

You find out who your real friends are. They show up even though you don’t always.

Your relationship is tested, more than ever, as you each take on new roles. But you still choose each other at the end of everyday.

Your new body is still healing and still feels a bit foreign. The way it provides for your baby and keeps going day after day makes you love it and respect it more than you can critique it.

And your new identity is sometimes the most empowering title, and sometimes the one you don’t want to identify with.

I took this picture yesterday morning. After a hard night the night before and in the middle of a rough morning. I was at my breaking point, crying while feeding and texting Chase saying, “I can’t do this.” Because at the time I didn’t want to.

I looked back at this picture after taking it, though, and saw “Mama” written on my shirt. And the chain of my necklace tucked beneath my Mama shirt that says “Eli” on the pendant. And I remembered that I not only CAN do it, but that I AM doing it. And WILL continue to do it.

And that’s right there is what makes motherhood powerful. The ability to rally. The second, third, and fourth wind that we always muster up. That, right when we want to quit, we simply don’t.

The emptiness, tests, losses, and changes all make up a strong, relentless, and powerful new identity: Mama."

📷: @fittestcore

node.text:
“It’s waiting for your milk to come in
It’s sore, hard boobs and cluster feeding. 
You’re told it’s natural, but it feels so unnatural. 
It’s sore nipples and nipple creams. Nursing bras and nursing pads 
It’s pumping in the middle of the night, then cleaning and disinfecting, just to start all over again. 
It’s trying to get them to take a bottle. 
It’s a partner feeling helpless
It’s a bad latch and then it’s lactation consultants, tongue ties and lip ties
It’s not enough milk
so it’s supplements and supplementing and even more pumping
It’s warm compresses.
It’s too much milk
It’s leaking through your shirt and waking up with wet bedsheets, so then
It’s cold compresses. 
It’s side-lying, football hold, trying to remember which side to feed from next. 
It’s clogged ducts, fevers, Mastitis. Allergies and changing your diet.
It’s debating having that drink, taking that medication and using that product.
It’s nourishment. 
It’s loving skin to skin and then feeling touched out
It’s 'Are they getting enough?'
It’s stressfully watching every single oz you pump. 
It’s crying over spilled milk
It’s frustration
It’s some looks of judgement and some looks of empathy
It’s hormone fluctuation 
It’s fulfilling and beautiful. Affordable and convenient.
It’s a tiny hand reaching up for you. Touching your face or wrapping around your finger. 
Then it’s nails reaching up to scratch you.
It’s tiring. Being used as a pacifier. Never having a break. 
It’s physically demanding and mentally draining. 
It’s bonding. 
It’s wanting to stop and it’s not wanting to stop 
All at the same time."
@seasonsofpeaches

node.text:
Legs out for the win! This cutie is in treatment for club feet, and has to wear a bar and boot combo. Do we have any other clubfoot mamas here?!❤️
.
“Thank you so much for creating this swaddle! From day one, Sophia has had to be swaddled with her arms against her sides or she won’t sleep. We would not be able to swaddle her with her boots and bar without the legs out method! You have helped us sleep at night 🤍” @em__bry 

.
.
